#### Jackson County

Here are the listings for Jackson County:

1.  **Church of the Sacred Heart (Catholic)**
    *   **Image:** Church of the Sacred Heart (Catholic) (More images available)
    *   **Date Listed:** March 20, 1989 (NRHP Reference #: 89000157)
    *   **Location:** 9th St. and 4th Ave.
    *   **Coordinates:** 43°47′41″N 95°19′02″W﻿ / ﻿43.794722°N 95.317222°W﻿ / 43.794722; -95.317222 (Church of the Sacred Heart (Catholic))
    *   **Description:** This church in [Heron Lake](/Heron_Lake,_Minnesota) is recognized as the largest and most elaborately appointed early 20th-century church in southwest Minnesota. Built between 1920 and 1921, it showcases [Neoclassical](/Neoclassical_architecture) and [Baroque Revival architecture](/Baroque_Revival_architecture) influences and stands as a testament to the community's religious and cultural importance.

2.  **District No. 92 School**
    *   **Image:** District No. 92 School
    *   **Date Listed:** October 27, 1988 (NRHP Reference #: 88002082)
    *   **Location:** County Highway 9
    *   **Coordinates:** 43°33′59″N 95°02′07″W﻿ / ﻿43.566326°N 95.035182°W﻿ / 43.566326; -95.035182 (District No. 92 School)
    *   **Description:** This unusual octagonal schoolhouse, built in 1906 in [Jackson](/Jackson,_Minnesota), is one of only two surviving examples in Minnesota inspired by the [octagon house](/Octagon_house) concept promoted by [Orson Squire Fowler](/Orson_Squire_Fowler). It represents a unique approach to rural education architecture.

3.  **Jackson Commercial Historic District**
    *   **Image:** Jackson Commercial Historic District (More images available)
    *   **Date Listed:** December 17, 1987 (NRHP Reference #: 87002155)
    *   **Location:** 2nd St. between Sheridan and White Sts.
    *   **Coordinates:** 43°37′18″N 94°59′16″W﻿ / ﻿43.621594°N 94.987713°W﻿ / 43.621594; -94.987713 (Jackson Commercial Historic District)
    *   **Description:** This cohesive commercial district in [Jackson](/Jackson,_Minnesota) chronicles the small businesses that formed the core of a late 19th and early 20th-century railroad-based trade center. It includes 31 contributing properties constructed between 1880 and 1928, with seven specifically linked to the influential businessman Frank A. Matuska (1872–1947).

4.  **Jackson County Courthouse**
    *   **Image:** Jackson County Courthouse (Minnesota) (More images available)
    *   **Date Listed:** April 13, 1977 (NRHP Reference #: 77000747)
    *   **Location:** 413 4th St.
    *   **Coordinates:** 43°37′16″N 94°59′25″W﻿ / ﻿43.621223°N 94.990159°W﻿ / 43.621223; -94.990159 (Jackson County Courthouse)
    *   **Description:** The 1908 courthouse in [Jackson](/Jackson,_Minnesota) has long served as the seat of county government and remains a local landmark. It is distinguished by its consistent [Neoclassical architecture](/Neoclassical_architecture) and the artistic elements that extend from its exterior to its interior.

5.  **George M. Moore Farmstead**
    *   **Image:** George M. Moore Farmstead
    *   **Date Listed:** January 7, 1987 (NRHP Reference #: 86003604)
    *   **Location:** Off County Highway 4
    *   **Coordinates:** 43°30′53″N 95°04′45″W﻿ / ﻿43.514722°N 95.079167°W﻿ / 43.514722; -95.079167 (George M. Moore Farmstead)
    *   **Description:** Also known as Moorland, this farmstead near [Jackson](/Jackson,_Minnesota) features Jackson County's most architecturally sophisticated farmhouse, along with two other [American Craftsman](/American_Craftsman) buildings, all constructed in 1917. It represents a significant example of early 20th-century rural architecture.

6.  **Robertson Park Site**
    *   **Image:** Robertson Park Site
    *   **Date Listed:** August 1, 1980 (NRHP Reference #: 80002082)
    *   **Location:** Address restricted [11]
    *   **Description:** This habitation site near [Jackson](/Jackson,_Minnesota) is estimated to have been occupied from approximately 100 BCE to 800 CE, offering valuable archaeological data on prehistoric life in the region.

